{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500341"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:11:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:11:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1629"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1629"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.14,0.74,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1629"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30530"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1629"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1629"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16472"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3815"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3819"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17529"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46736"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30530"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with amenorrhoea. She states that she has had a stressful month as she has recently broken up with her boyfriend. She had taken up ultramarathon running 6 months ago and has reported an irregular period during this time. Her last menstrual period was 12 weeks ago. She has not experienced any nausea, vomiting or breast tenderness. A urinary pregnancy test is positive. A pelvic ultrasound is arranged and this shows an intrauterine gestational sac with fetal pole.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What is the likely gestational age of the fetus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No pregnancy identified","2-4 weeks","6-10 weeks","14-20 weeks","28-32 weeks"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe images show a retroflexed, anteverted uterus with surrounding hyperechoic ring (double decidual sign) and fetal pole. This is consistent with an early intrauterine pregnancy of approximately \u003Cstrong\u003E6\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eweeks\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Egestation\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a trans-abdominal scan (TAS) and it is not uncommon that a fetal heart rate is not detected - however, no determination of the viability of the pregnancy can be made until a transvaginal scan (TVS) is performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo confirm the gestational age, the measurement of the fetal pole or crown-rump-length (CRL) is required. A TVS would be performed to accurately measure and date the pregnancy as well as assess for the presence of a fetal heart rate (FHR). If no FHR is seen, a repeat scan in 7-10 days is requested.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt less than 4 weeks gestation, the uterus often appears empty and there are normally no ultrasound findings to report. In these images we can see a gestational sac with fetal pole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gestational sac is first visible around 4 weeks gestation, with a yolk sac seen from about 5 weeks and fetal heart rate able to be detected on ultrasound from 6 weeks gestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrom 6-7 weeks the fetal pole can be visualised, the FHR can be detected and the gestational sac is approximately 10mm in diameter. At 8-9 weeks gestation, fetal limb buds are evident and at 9-10 weeks gestation, the fetus can be seen to be moving with a FHR between 170-180bpm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The gestational sac is first visible around 4 weeks gestation, with a yolk sac seen from about 5 weeks and fetal heart rate able to be detected on ultrasound from 6 weeks gestation."],"references":["Australian Standards for Ultrasound in Medicine. Guidelines for the Performance of First Trimester Ultrasound. Revised April 2021. https://www.asum.com.au/files/public/SoP/curver/Obs-Gynae/Guidelines-for-the-Performance-of-First-Trimester-Ultrasound.pdf. Accessed 14/9/2021","Gaillard, F., Muzio, B. Early Pregnancy. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org. (accessed on 14 Sep 2021) https://radiopaedia.org/articles/1255"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16472"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1629"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18433"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18434"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18433"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a42839f7-910b-4926-a585-c6ad76102078.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a42839f7-910b-4926-a585-c6ad76102078.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":524}},{"type":"media","id":"18434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18434"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cc2528b7-7a87-4d60-a887-287b32f780cc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cc2528b7-7a87-4d60-a887-287b32f780cc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":500,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/16472"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-12-01T16:51:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-12T18:23:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":